  <info><![CDATA[## WHAT IS IT?

A simple model of habit and brand loyalty. 200 customers with small daily budgets repeatedly buy from one product category stocked by 8 competing brands (Zappa, Kova, Nuvo, Fizzo, Blip, Gusto, Vibe, Munch). Each customer keeps a private loyalty score for every brand; those scores build when a brand is bought, fade when it is not, and steer the next choice - so brands drift, a leader emerges, and loyalties lock in or switch, none of it hard-coded.

It is the single-category version of a brand-choice model: the classic setting (Guadagni & Little calibrated their model on one category, coffee), stripped of anything not central to loyalty dynamics.


## HOW IT WORKS

Each customer holds one **loyalty score** per brand (any number, starting near zero) and one **shopping probability**.

Each tick is one day:

1. **Deliveries.** Any order in transit counts down and arrives when its lead time expires.

2. **Budget.** Each wallet refills to a personal base (5-15 dollars) give or take 10% noise.

3. **Shopping.** With probability equal to its shopping habit, a customer makes a trip. Choice is **habitual by default**: each in-stock brand gets a softmax weight `exp(beta-loyalty x score)`, competing with a fixed-weight no-buy option, and one is drawn in proportion to its weight - so the strongest score usually wins and price is ignored. On a minority of occasions the customer **deliberates**, adding `beta-price x price-satisfaction` so price re-enters; this fires with probability `deliberation-prob`, and always when its favourite brand is out of stock. A chosen brand is bought in a quantity of 1..`max-units`, subject to stock and money.

4. **Learning.** A purchase carries a **reward** in [0,1], blended from how cheap the brand was and how much of the wanted amount was bought. The chosen brand's score moves by `loyalty-gain x (reward - reward-neutral)` - up if satisfying, down if not - and after a satisfying buy the rivals' scores drop a little. Getting the wanted amount raises the shopping habit; falling short lowers it.

5. **Forgetting.** Every score then fades toward zero by a small fraction, so a habit lasts only if it keeps being renewed. No lead is permanent, and a shock can unseat a leader.

6. **Reordering.** Each brand restocks with an order-up-to rule and a random 1-5 day lead time.

The choice is plain reinforcement learning: scores plus a softmax, with no probabilities or log-odds in between. Note the shop pays 70% of the *catalog* price per unit and a sale cuts the shelf price 35%, so a discounted unit sells **below cost** - volume rises but margin turns negative.


## HOW TO USE IT

Press **setup**, then **go**. To run a sale, press a brand button; **discount-days** sets how long it lasts. Nothing goes on sale on its own.

**Market Share per Brand (%)** - each brand's share of the day's units. Watch a leader pull ahead.

**Cumulative Sales / Profit per Brand ($)** - running totals. Line them up against a sale: a brand's sales line steepens while it is discounted, but its profit line stalls or dips, because discounted units sell below cost.

**Current Shelf Stock** - units per brand; a bar turns **magenta** while that brand is on sale.

Monitors show total sales and profit, **% broke today** (customers who wanted to shop but could not afford it), **on sale now**, and each brand's price (with a SALE flag when discounted).


## THINGS TO NOTICE

A leader **emerges** even though no rule picks one, and running setup again can crown a different brand - the outcome turns on early, chance events (**path dependence**). With eight brands the market stays competitive: expect a leader around a quarter to a third of sales, not a runaway monopoly.

A sale trades volume for margin: it lifts a brand's share and cumulative sales while its cumulative profit line flattens or falls. Because forgetting loosens old habits, some customers tempted by the sale keep the brand afterwards, so the effect can outlive the discount.

Shelf stock shows the classic bullwhip: a run empties a shelf, a big reorder overshoots, then drains again.


## THINGS TO TRY

Set `loyalty-forget-rate` to 0 and the market **freezes** after an early transient: scores never fade, so whoever leads early stays. Raise it and loyalties churn.

Lower `deliberation-prob` toward 0 for almost purely habitual customers whose favourites lock in early; raise it to let price and stockouts stir the market. Push `beta-loyalty` up for stickier, more winner-take-all brands, or `loyalty-gain` up for faster lock-in.

Put a brand on sale and watch its share climb while the gap opens between its sales and profit lines. Try deeper (`brand-discount-rate`) or longer (`discount-days`) sales.

Lower `num-brands` for a clearer winner (fewer brands split the market less); cut the budgets to make % broke climb.


## EXTENDING THE MODEL

Add word-of-mouth: nudge a customer's scores toward those of others, so bandwagons can form - the one large mechanism left out. Draw the personal parameters (forgetting, loyalty gain, deliberation) per customer, so habitual anchors and restless switchers coexist. Or restore several categories sharing one wallet, to study how a tight budget makes categories compete.


## NETLOGO FEATURES

Brands and customers are two invisible breeds. Each customer's loyalties are a plain list of scores, one per brand. Choice is a softmax turned into a draw by a small reusable `weighted-pick` reporter, with the no-buy option carried as a `nobody` entry in the option list. Reinforcement and forgetting are ordinary arithmetic on the scores - no `logit`/`logistic` - and the favourite brand is just `position (max loyalties) loyalties`.


## RELATED MODELS

* Simple Economy - money changing hands under simple rules.
* El Farol - agents adapting choice probabilities from experience.


## CREDITS AND REFERENCES

The habitual-by-default rule, reward-scaled loyalty, and forgetting follow the habit-as-reinforcement-learning account:

* Wood, W., & Rünger, D. (2016). Psychology of habit. *Annual Review of Psychology, 67*, 289-314.
* Judah, G., Gardner, B., Kenward, M. G., DeStavola, B., & Michie, S. (2018). Exploratory study of the impact of perceived reward on habit formation. *BMC Psychology, 6*, 62.

The loyalty-as-smoothed-past-purchases mechanism descends from Guadagni, P. M., & Little, J. D. C. (1983), and the self-reinforcing lock-in it produces from Arthur, W. B. (1989). Choice follows the multinomial-logit tradition (McFadden); the supply oscillation reproduces the Beer Distribution Game (Sterman, 1989).

NetLogo:

* Wilensky, U. (1999). NetLogo. Center for Connected Learning and Computer-Based Modeling, Northwestern University, Evanston, IL. http://ccl.northwestern.edu/netlogo/]]></info>
